issue.title: Implement AbstractImage.get_renditions()
issue.body:
Where we want to generate multiple renditions for the same image (e.g. from a `{% picture  %}` tag), we should have a method to do that more efficiently. The aim is to do the following things once for the entire set, instead of once for every rendition:
- Query the cache (using `cache.get_many()` instead of `cache.get()`)
- Query the database (if not present in cache) (using `QuerySet.filter()` instead of `QuerySet.get()`
- Read the original image file into memory once (The largest improvement)
- Save newly created renditions to the database (using `QuerySet.bulk_create()` instead of `QuerySet.create()`)
- Update the cache (using `cache.set_many()` instead of `cache.set()`)

comment.body: @gasman Okay, this design is now something I'm a bit happier with.... I have broken down `get_renditions()` in a similar way to `get_rendition()`... with most of the custom code moving to `find_existing_renditions()` (the 'many' equivalent of `find_existing_rendtion`). This way `get_rendition()` still hits all of the same methods it did before, but the default `find_existing_rendition()` implementation can piggy-back off `find_existing_renditions()` to reduce code duplication.

labels.name: component:Choosers
labels.description: Modal choosers for Page, Snippet and other models

issue.body:
It would be great if you could filter Pages on PageChooserPanel using a queryset.

Something like:

```
PageChooserPanel('link_page', queryset=EventPage.objects.live().descendant_of(events_index)),
```

comment.body:
Another option to achieve this sort of thing is [Proxy models].
 
1. Define a proxy page model, subclassing the page type you're actually interested in (e.g. `news.ArticlePage`).
2. Add a custom manager to the model and override `get_queryset()` to apply any filters you need.
3. Add `is_creatable = False` to the model to prevent it from being used for other things.
4. Pass the **lone** (important) proxy model to the chooser using the `page_type` argument.

issue.title: Add `read_only` and `read_only_on_update` options to `FieldPanel`
issue.body:
Related issue/discussion: #2893 Supersedes: #6194 and #6067 ### When would you use these options? When you want to display a model field value without it ever being editable, use `read_only=True` in the `FieldPanel` constructor, e.g. `FieldPanel("slug", read_only=True)` When you want to allow an initial value to be set on creation, but prevent that value from being changed in later updates, use `read_only_on_update=True` in the `FieldPanel` constructor, e.g. `FieldPanel("slug", read_only_on_update=True)` ### What is displayed in read-only mode? Following the "Form follows function" design principle, if we don't intend for the value to be updated, there's no point in presenting the user with a form control (whether hidden, disabled or in any other special state). So, for read-only panels, we avoid adding fields to the (dynamically generated) `ModelForm`, and simplify the output. Instead of a form control, we render the field value in a `
` element, which looks a lot like a disabled `` element, but is screen-reader navigable in much the same way as a regular (non-disabled) input. While setting the `disabled` attribute on the Django form field would grant us similar protection, not including a field in the form at all gives us a cast-iron guarantee that field values included in POSTed data will not be applied to the model (unexpected values are simply ignored and will never be included in `form.cleaned_data`). Validation isn't applied to non-fields values either. ### Can I use it to display arbitrary attribute values? I'm afraid not. `FieldPanel` has a pre-existing restriction that allows it to be used for model fields only (which makes sense when you consider the name). For arbitrary model instance values, it makes sense to introduce an entirely new panel type, which will contributed via a separate PR. ### Are all field types supported? Yes, but displaying chunks of user-controlled HTML mid-form is a touch on the risky side so, for `StreamField` or `RichTextField` values, a text-only representation is extracted from the HTML (using the same method as used for the 'compare revisions' view). If for any reason you don't like the default representation of a field value, you can override the `format_value_for_display()` method to control what is rendered. ``` class KeyIngredientsPanel(FieldPanel): """ A custom FieldPanel for use with the 'key_ingredients' ParentalManyToManyField """ def format_value_for_display(self, value): # Show a comma-separate list of ingredients when in read-only mode return ", ".join(obj.get_listing_summary() for obj in value.all()) ``` ### How it looks As children of a `MultiFieldPanel`: As top-level `FieldPanel` instances:

issue.title: Improve support for proxy models
issue.body:
Related issues: #4973, #2480
Supersedes: #5202

Going for complete proxy model support here, instead of just for Page models (although, Page models are where most changes are needed)

Before these changes:

- You could register a non-page proxy model via modeladmin, the proxy model permissions would be assignable via the Group add/edit views, and those same permissions would be used to protect view access
- You could register a proxy model as a Snippet, but only the **concrete/parent** model permissions would be assignable via the Group add/edit views, and would be used to protect view access
- You could define a proxy Page type. But, when creating instances of that page type, the `content_type` value would be set to that of the **concrete/parent** model, meaning only instances of that model could be accessed via `Page.specific`, `Page.specific_deferred`, or `PageQuerySet.specific()`
- Checking of `Page.subpage_types` and `Page.parent_page_types` would only recognise **concrete/parent** types, leading to unexpected failures.

With these changes:

- Support in modeladmin remains unchanged, but is now tested.
- When registering a proxy model as a Snippet, the permissions for the proxy model are correctly registered, are assignable via the Group add/edit views, and are used to protect view access. (NOTE: will need outlining under upgrade considerations in release notes).
- When creating proxy Page type instances, the `content_type` value is correctly set to that of the proxy model, and instances of that model class are correctly returned by `Page.specific`, `Page.specific_deferred`, or `PageQuerySet.specific()`. Where possible, these methods have been upgraded to take advantage of the reduced need for 'table hopping' associated with MTI.
- Checking of `Page.subpage_types` and `Page.parent_page_types` works correctly

issue.title: Log entry managers use ContentType.objects.get_for_model() inconsistently

labels.name: status:Unconfirmed
labels.description: Issue, usually a bug, that has not yet been validated as a confirmed problem.

issue.body:
### Issue Summary

When using `BaseLogEntryManager.log_action()` to save a new entry to the database,`ContentType.objects.get_for_model()` is called using the `for_concrete_model= False` option, which will result in a `ContentType` for a proxy model being returned (when `instance` is an instance of a proxy model).

See: https://github.com/wagtail/wagtail/blob/main/wagtail/models/audit_log.py#L109-L111

In contrast, when using ` BaseLogEntryManager.get_for_model()` to retrieve actions relevant to a model, `ContentType.objects.get_for_model()`  is used without specifying a `for_concrete_model` value, and so a default value of `False`

See: https://github.com/wagtail/wagtail/blob/main/wagtail/models/audit_log.py#L128

Finally, in `ModelLogEntryManager.get_for_instance()`, the approach turns again to providing `for_concrete_model= False`.

See: https://github.com/wagtail/wagtail/blob/main/wagtail/models/audit_log.py#L275-L277

This inconsistency could produce unexpected results when logging and recovering log instances.

### Suggested fix

If you're actioning something for a proxy model instance, you're really actioning something for the concrete instance and all/any proxy variations, because all variations share the same underlying database record. I feel the correct behaviour would be to consistently use  `ContentType.objects.get_for_model(for_concrete_model=True)` instead, so that the concrete model's `ContentType` is used every time.

issue.title: Implement AbstractImage.get_renditions()
issue.body:
Where we want to generate multiple renditions for the same image (e.g. from a `{% picture  %}` tag), we should have a method to do that more efficiently. The aim is to do the following things once for the entire set, instead of once for every rendition:
- Query the cache (using `cache.get_many()` instead of `cache.get()`)
- Query the database (if not present in cache) (using `QuerySet.filter()` instead of `QuerySet.get()`
- Read the original image file into memory once (The largest improvement)
- Save newly created renditions to the database (using `QuerySet.bulk_create()` instead of `QuerySet.create()`)
- Update the cache (using `cache.set_many()` instead of `cache.set()`)

Where we want to generate multiple renditions for the same image (e.g. from a `{% picture  %}` tag), we should have a method to do that more efficiently. The aim is to do the following things once for the entire set, instead of once for every rendition:
- Query the cache (using `cache.get_many()` instead of `cache.get()`)
- Query the database (if not present in cache) (using `QuerySet.filter()` instead of `QuerySet.get()`
- Read the original image file into memory once (The largest improvement)
- Save newly created renditions to the database (using `QuerySet.bulk_create()` instead of `QuerySet.create()`)
- Update the cache (using `cache.set_many()` instead of `cache.set()`)

comment.body: @gasman Okay, this design is now something I'm a bit happier with.... I have broken down `get_renditions()` in a similar way to `get_rendition()`... with most of the custom code moving to `find_existing_renditions()` (the 'many' equivalent of `find_existing_rendtion`). This way `get_rendition()` still hits all of the same methods it did before, but the default `find_existing_rendition()` implementation can piggy-back off `find_existing_renditions()` to reduce code duplication.

labels.description: Modal choosers for Page, Snippet and other models

issue.body:
It would be great if you could filter Pages on PageChooserPanel using a queryset.

Something like:

```
PageChooserPanel('link_page', queryset=EventPage.objects.live().descendant_of(events_index)),
```

comment.body:
Another option to achieve this sort of thing is [Proxy models].
 
1. Define a proxy page model, subclassing the page type you're actually interested in (e.g. `news.ArticlePage`).
2. Add a custom manager to the model and override `get_queryset()` to apply any filters you need.
3. Add `is_creatable = False` to the model to prevent it from being used for other things.
4. Pass the **lone** (important) proxy model to the chooser using the `page_type` argument.

issue.title: Add `read_only` and `read_only_on_update` options to `FieldPanel`
issue.body:
Related issue/discussion: #2893 Supersedes: #6194 and #6067 ### When would you use these options? When you want to display a model field value without it ever being editable, use `read_only=True` in the `FieldPanel` constructor, e.g. `FieldPanel("slug", read_only=True)` When you want to allow an initial value to be set on creation, but prevent that value from being changed in later updates, use `read_only_on_update=True` in the `FieldPanel` constructor, e.g. `FieldPanel("slug", read_only_on_update=True)` ### What is displayed in read-only mode? Following the "Form follows function" design principle, if we don't intend for the value to be updated, there's no point in presenting the user with a form control (whether hidden, disabled or in any other special state). So, for read-only panels, we avoid adding fields to the (dynamically generated) `ModelForm`, and simplify the output. Instead of a form control, we render the field value in a `
` element, which looks a lot like a disabled `` element, but is screen-reader navigable in much the same way as a regular (non-disabled) input. While setting the `disabled` attribute on the Django form field would grant us similar protection, not including a field in the form at all gives us a cast-iron guarantee that field values included in POSTed data will not be applied to the model (unexpected values are simply ignored and will never be included in `form.cleaned_data`). Validation isn't applied to non-fields values either. ### Can I use it to display arbitrary attribute values? I'm afraid not. `FieldPanel` has a pre-existing restriction that allows it to be used for model fields only (which makes sense when you consider the name). For arbitrary model instance values, it makes sense to introduce an entirely new panel type, which will contributed via a separate PR. ### Are all field types supported? Yes, but displaying chunks of user-controlled HTML mid-form is a touch on the risky side so, for `StreamField` or `RichTextField` values, a text-only representation is extracted from the HTML (using the same method as used for the 'compare revisions' view). If for any reason you don't like the default representation of a field value, you can override the `format_value_for_display()` method to control what is rendered. ``` class KeyIngredientsPanel(FieldPanel): """ A custom FieldPanel for use with the 'key_ingredients' ParentalManyToManyField """ def format_value_for_display(self, value): # Show a comma-separate list of ingredients when in read-only mode return ", ".join(obj.get_listing_summary() for obj in value.all()) ``` ### How it looks As children of a `MultiFieldPanel`: As top-level `FieldPanel` instances:

issue.title: Improve support for proxy models
issue.body:
Related issues: #4973, #2480
Supersedes: #5202

Going for complete proxy model support here, instead of just for Page models (although, Page models are where most changes are needed)

Before these changes:

- You could register a non-page proxy model via modeladmin, the proxy model permissions would be assignable via the Group add/edit views, and those same permissions would be used to protect view access
- You could register a proxy model as a Snippet, but only the **concrete/parent** model permissions would be assignable via the Group add/edit views, and would be used to protect view access
- You could define a proxy Page type. But, when creating instances of that page type, the `content_type` value would be set to that of the **concrete/parent** model, meaning only instances of that model could be accessed via `Page.specific`, `Page.specific_deferred`, or `PageQuerySet.specific()`
- Checking of `Page.subpage_types` and `Page.parent_page_types` would only recognise **concrete/parent** types, leading to unexpected failures.

With these changes:

- Support in modeladmin remains unchanged, but is now tested.
- When registering a proxy model as a Snippet, the permissions for the proxy model are correctly registered, are assignable via the Group add/edit views, and are used to protect view access. (NOTE: will need outlining under upgrade considerations in release notes).
- When creating proxy Page type instances, the `content_type` value is correctly set to that of the proxy model, and instances of that model class are correctly returned by `Page.specific`, `Page.specific_deferred`, or `PageQuerySet.specific()`. Where possible, these methods have been upgraded to take advantage of the reduced need for 'table hopping' associated with MTI.
- Checking of `Page.subpage_types` and `Page.parent_page_types` works correctly

comment.body:
> Reference index: Any references to an object from a proxy model instance are really references from the concrete model instance, as it's that object's data that is used for any/all proxy representations - they shouldn't count as individual/separate references. Therefore, I feel content_type on that model should also be storing the concrete model type, but that is not how it works currently. Should this also be updated?

These concerns are addressed in #9665

issue.title: Improve support for proxy models
issue.body:
Related issues: #4973, #2480
Supersedes: #5202

Going for complete proxy model support here, instead of just for Page models (although, Page models are where most changes are needed)

Before these changes:

- You could register a non-page proxy model via modeladmin, the proxy model permissions would be assignable via the Group add/edit views, and those same permissions would be used to protect view access
- You could register a proxy model as a Snippet, but only the **concrete/parent** model permissions would be assignable via the Group add/edit views, and would be used to protect view access
- You could define a proxy Page type. But, when creating instances of that page type, the `content_type` value would be set to that of the **concrete/parent** model, meaning only instances of that model could be accessed via `Page.specific`, `Page.specific_deferred`, or `PageQuerySet.specific()`
- Checking of `Page.subpage_types` and `Page.parent_page_types` would only recognise **concrete/parent** types, leading to unexpected failures.

With these changes:

- Support in modeladmin remains unchanged, but is now tested.
- When registering a proxy model as a Snippet, the permissions for the proxy model are correctly registered, are assignable via the Group add/edit views, and are used to protect view access. (NOTE: will need outlining under upgrade considerations in release notes).
- When creating proxy Page type instances, the `content_type` value is correctly set to that of the proxy model, and instances of that model class are correctly returned by `Page.specific`, `Page.specific_deferred`, or `PageQuerySet.specific()`. Where possible, these methods have been upgraded to take advantage of the reduced need for 'table hopping' associated with MTI.
- Checking of `Page.subpage_types` and `Page.parent_page_types` works correctly

issue.title: Log entry managers use ContentType.objects.get_for_model() inconsistently

labels.name: status:Unconfirmed
labels.description: Issue, usually a bug, that has not yet been validated as a confirmed problem.

issue.body:
### Issue Summary

When using `BaseLogEntryManager.log_action()` to save a new entry to the database,`ContentType.objects.get_for_model()` is called using the `for_concrete_model= False` option, which will result in a `ContentType` for a proxy model being returned (when `instance` is an instance of a proxy model).

See: https://github.com/wagtail/wagtail/blob/main/wagtail/models/audit_log.py#L109-L111

In contrast, when using ` BaseLogEntryManager.get_for_model()` to retrieve actions relevant to a model, `ContentType.objects.get_for_model()`  is used without specifying a `for_concrete_model` value, and so a default value of `False`

See: https://github.com/wagtail/wagtail/blob/main/wagtail/models/audit_log.py#L128

Finally, in `ModelLogEntryManager.get_for_instance()`, the approach turns again to providing `for_concrete_model= False`.

See: https://github.com/wagtail/wagtail/blob/main/wagtail/models/audit_log.py#L275-L277

This inconsistency could produce unexpected results when logging and recovering log instances.

### Suggested fix

If you're actioning something for a proxy model instance, you're really actioning something for the concrete instance and all/any proxy variations, because all variations share the same underlying database record. I feel the correct behaviour would be to consistently use  `ContentType.objects.get_for_model(for_concrete_model=True)` instead, so that the concrete model's `ContentType` is used every time.

- Save newly created renditions to the database (using `QuerySet.bulk_create()` instead of `QuerySet.create()`)
- Update the cache (using `cache.set_many()` instead of `cache.set()`)

Where we want to generate multiple renditions for the same image (e.g. from a `{% picture  %}` tag), we should have a method to do that more efficiently. The aim is to do the following things once for the entire set, instead of once for every rendition:
- Query the cache (using `cache.get_many()` instead of `cache.get()`)

- Read the original image file into memory once (The largest improvement)
- Save newly created renditions to the database (using `QuerySet.bulk_create()` instead of `QuerySet.create()`)
- Update the cache (using `cache.set_many()` instead of `cache.set()`)

issue.title: Add `read_only` and `read_only_on_update` options to `FieldPanel`
issue.body:
Related issue/discussion: #2893 Supersedes: #6194 and #6067 ### When would you use these options? When you want to display a model field value without it ever being editable, use `read_only=True` in the `FieldPanel` constructor, e.g. `FieldPanel("slug", read_only=True)` When you want to allow an initial value to be set on creation, but prevent that value from being changed in later updates, use `read_only_on_update=True` in the `FieldPanel` constructor, e.g. `FieldPanel("slug", read_only_on_update=True)` ### What is displayed in read-only mode? Following the "Form follows function" design principle, if we don't intend for the value to be updated, there's no point in presenting the user with a form control (whether hidden, disabled or in any other special state). So, for read-only panels, we avoid adding fields to the (dynamically generated) `ModelForm`, and simplify the output. Instead of a form control, we render the field value in a `
` element, which looks a lot like a disabled `` element, but is screen-reader navigable in much the same way as a regular (non-disabled) input. While setting the `disabled` attribute on the Django form field would grant us similar protection, not including a field in the form at all gives us a cast-iron guarantee that field values included in POSTed data will not be applied to the model (unexpected values are simply ignored and will never be included in `form.cleaned_data`). Validation isn't applied to non-fields values either. ### Can I use it to display arbitrary attribute values? I'm afraid not. `FieldPanel` has a pre-existing restriction that allows it to be used for model fields only (which makes sense when you consider the name). For arbitrary model instance values, it makes sense to introduce an entirely new panel type, which will contributed via a separate PR. ### Are all field types supported? Yes, but displaying chunks of user-controlled HTML mid-form is a touch on the risky side so, for `StreamField` or `RichTextField` values, a text-only representation is extracted from the HTML (using the same method as used for the 'compare revisions' view). If for any reason you don't like the default representation of a field value, you can override the `format_value_for_display()` method to control what is rendered. ``` class KeyIngredientsPanel(FieldPanel): """ A custom FieldPanel for use with the 'key_ingredients' ParentalManyToManyField """ def format_value_for_display(self, value): # Show a comma-separate list of ingredients when in read-only mode return ", ".join(obj.get_listing_summary() for obj in value.all()) ``` ### How it looks As children of a `MultiFieldPanel`: As top-level `FieldPanel` instances:

issue.title: Improve support for proxy models
issue.body:
Related issues: #4973, #2480
Supersedes: #5202

Going for complete proxy model support here, instead of just for Page models (although, Page models are where most changes are needed)

Before these changes:

- You could register a non-page proxy model via modeladmin, the proxy model permissions would be assignable via the Group add/edit views, and those same permissions would be used to protect view access
- You could register a proxy model as a Snippet, but only the **concrete/parent** model permissions would be assignable via the Group add/edit views, and would be used to protect view access
- You could define a proxy Page type. But, when creating instances of that page type, the `content_type` value would be set to that of the **concrete/parent** model, meaning only instances of that model could be accessed via `Page.specific`, `Page.specific_deferred`, or `PageQuerySet.specific()`
- Checking of `Page.subpage_types` and `Page.parent_page_types` would only recognise **concrete/parent** types, leading to unexpected failures.

With these changes:

- Support in modeladmin remains unchanged, but is now tested.
- When registering a proxy model as a Snippet, the permissions for the proxy model are correctly registered, are assignable via the Group add/edit views, and are used to protect view access. (NOTE: will need outlining under upgrade considerations in release notes).
- When creating proxy Page type instances, the `content_type` value is correctly set to that of the proxy model, and instances of that model class are correctly returned by `Page.specific`, `Page.specific_deferred`, or `PageQuerySet.specific()`. Where possible, these methods have been upgraded to take advantage of the reduced need for 'table hopping' associated with MTI.
- Checking of `Page.subpage_types` and `Page.parent_page_types` works correctly

comment.body:

Therefore, I feel content_type on that model should also be storing the concrete model type, but that is not how it works currently. Should this also be updated?

These concerns are addressed in #9665

issue.title: Log entry managers use ContentType.objects.get_for_model() inconsistently

labels.name: status:Unconfirmed
labels.description: Issue, usually a bug, that has not yet been validated as a confirmed problem.

issue.body:
### Issue Summary

When using `BaseLogEntryManager.log_action()` to save a new entry to the database,`ContentType.objects.get_for_model()` is called using the `for_concrete_model= False` option, which will result in a `ContentType` for a proxy model being returned (when `instance` is an instance of a proxy model).

See: https://github.com/wagtail/wagtail/blob/main/wagtail/models/audit_log.py#L109-L111

In contrast, when using ` BaseLogEntryManager.get_for_model()` to retrieve actions relevant to a model, `ContentType.objects.get_for_model()`  is used without specifying a `for_concrete_model` value, and so a default value of `False`

See: https://github.com/wagtail/wagtail/blob/main/wagtail/models/audit_log.py#L128

Finally, in `ModelLogEntryManager.get_for_instance()`, the approach turns again to providing `for_concrete_model= False`.

See: https://github.com/wagtail/wagtail/blob/main/wagtail/models/audit_log.py#L275-L277

This inconsistency could produce unexpected results when logging and recovering log instances.

### Suggested fix

If you're actioning something for a proxy model instance, you're really actioning something for the concrete instance and all/any proxy variations, because all variations share the same underlying database record. I feel the correct behaviour would be to consistently use  `ContentType.objects.get_for_model(for_concrete_model=True)` instead, so that the concrete model's `ContentType` is used every time.

Fix disabled style on StreamField add button

Fixes #9512

An `opacity: 0.2` style is defined for the disabled button state, but the `opacity: 1` hover style takes precedence over it. As a result, the only time it kicks in - on media with hover support - is when the StreamField does NOT have hover / focus, which would ordinarily be the time when the button is hidden entirely.

Fix this by adding hover states to the `&[disabled]` case, to match the order of precedence for the normal button state.
